{"parse":{"title":"Opus signinum","pageid":6034513,"revid":804619803,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Canal_Italica.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Canal_Italica.jpg/220px-Canal_Italica.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"150\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Canal_Italica.jpg/330px-Canal_Italica.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Canal_Italica.jpg/440px-Canal_Italica.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"787\" data-file-height=\"536\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Canal_Italica.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>An example of opus signinum: The <a href=\"/wiki/Aqueduct_(water_supply)\" title=\"Aqueduct (water supply)\">aqueduct</a> of It\u00e1lica near <a href=\"/wiki/Seville\" title=\"Seville\">Seville</a>.</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg/220px-Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"220\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg/330px-Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg/440px-Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2200\" data-file-height=\"2200\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Haselburg_opus_signinum.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>opus signinum</i>-piece from the <i>Roman Villa Haselburg</i>, near <a href=\"/wiki/H%C3%B6chst_im_Odenwald\" title=\"H\u00f6chst im Odenwald\">H\u00f6chst im Odenwald</a></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Opus_Signinum.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Opus_Signinum.JPG/220px-Opus_Signinum.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Opus_Signinum.JPG/330px-Opus_Signinum.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Opus_Signinum.JPG/440px-Opus_Signinum.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"1024\" data-file-height=\"768\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Opus_Signinum.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>reconstructed <i>opus signinum</i> in the <a href=\"/wiki/European_Archaeological_Park_of_Bliesbruck-Reinheim\" title=\"European Archaeological Park of Bliesbruck-Reinheim\">European Archaeological Park of Bliesbruck-Reinheim</a></div></div></div>\n<p><b>Opus signinum</b> ('cocciopesto' in modern Italian) is a building material used in <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Rome\" title=\"Ancient Rome\">ancient Rome</a>. It is  made of tiles broken up into very small pieces, mixed with mortar, and then beaten down with a rammer.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Pliny in his <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_History_(Pliny)\" title=\"Natural History (Pliny)\">Natural History</a> describes its manufacture: \"Even broken pottery has been utilized; it being found that, beaten to powder, and tempered with lime, it becomes more solid and durable than other substances of a similar nature; forming the cement known as the \"Signine\" composition, so extensively employed for even making the pavements of houses.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Pliny's use of the term \"Signine\" references \"Signia (modern Segni), the name of a town in Latium which was famous for its tiles.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span id=\"Origins.2C_spread.2C_disuse\"></span><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origins,_spread,_disuse\">Origins, spread, disuse</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opus_signinum&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origins, spread, disuse\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The technique began in North Africa, some time before 256 B.C., and spread north from there to Sicily and finally to the Italian peninsula.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Floors of signinum are found extensively in the Punic towns of North Africa and commonly in the Hellenistic houses on Sicily.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> While some signinum pavements have been found in Rome, the technique is not common there.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Vitruvius\" title=\"Vitruvius\">Vitruvius</a> describes the process of laying a floor, whether signinum or mosaic.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> The trend began in the 1st century BC, proliferating in private homes as well as public buildings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> By the 2nd century, opus signinum would give way to more patterned styles of pavement.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opus_signinum&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Sign\u012bnum Opus. Harry Thurston Peck, Harpers Dictionary of Classical Antiquities (1898). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.02.0137:book=35:chapter=46&amp;highlight=signinum%2Copus\">[1]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://old.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus:text:1999.02.0137&amp;layout=&amp;loc=35.46\">Pliny, Natural History, book 35, chapter 46</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/opus_signinum\">https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/opus_signinum</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">The Decorated Pavements of Morgantina II: The Opus Signinum. Author(s): Barbara Tsakirgis. <a href=\"/wiki/American_Journal_of_Archaeology\" title=\"American Journal of Archaeology\">American Journal of Archaeology</a>, Vol. 94, No. 3 (Jul., 1990), pp. 425-443. Archaeological Institute of America. <a href=\"/wiki/JSTOR\" title=\"JSTOR\">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/505795\">505795</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">The houses at Kerkouane on Cap Bon in Tunisia have opus signinum floors. The floors must date before 256 B.C., since the town was destroyed in that year by Regulus. Kerkouane I 79. H. Joyce, \"Form, Function and Technique in the Pavements of Delos and Pompeii,\" AJA 83 (1979) 259.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">For the signinum in the North African houses, see D. Harden, The Phoenicians (London 1962) 133-34; T. Carter, \"Western Phoenicians at Lepcis Magna,\" AJA 69 (1965) 128, pl. 33; M. Fantar, \"Pavimenta Punica et signe dit de Tanit dans les habitations de Kerkouane,\" Studi Magrebini 1 (1966) 57-65; M. Fantar, \"Les Pavements puniques,\" Les Dossiers de l'Archeologie (1978) 6-11; Kerkouane I 502-503; Kerkouane II; S. Lancel, \"Les Pavimenta Punica du quartier punique tardif de la colline de Byrsa,\" Cahiers des etudes anciennes 17 (1985) 157-77. For the signinum floors in Sicilian houses, see for Agrigento: R.P. Jones and E.A. Gardner, JHS 26 (1906) 207-12; E. Gabrici, NSc 1925, 425-37; for Avola: M.T. Curr\u00f2, BdA 51 (1966) 94; for Gela: D. Adames- teanu, NSc 1956, 346; for Heraclea Minoa: E. De Miro, Kokalos 12 (1966) 227; for Monte Iato: H.P. Isler, AntK 26 (1983) 39; for Solunto: M. deVos, BABESCH 50 (1975) 195- 224; for Syracuse: G. Gentili, NSc 1951, 156-57, NSc 1957, 282, 292; for Tindari: L. Bernab\u00f2 Brea, BdA 50 (1965) 207.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">M.L. Morricone Matini. Mosaici antichi in Italia: Pavimenti di signino repubblicani di Roma e dintorni (Rome 1971).</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Vitruvius/7*.html\">Marcus Vitruvius Pollio: de Architectura, Book VII</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">F. Sear. Roman Wall and Vault Mosaics. Heidelberg 1977</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Vassal, V. (2006). <i>Les Pavements d'Opus signinum&#160;: technique, d\u00e9cor, fonction architecturale</i>. Oxford.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Les+Pavements+d%27Opus+signinum+%3A+technique%2C+d%C3%A9cor%2C+fonction+architecturale&amp;rft.place=Oxford&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.aulast=Vassal&amp;rft.aufirst=V.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOpus+signinum\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opus_signinum&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1345\nCached time: 20180907231101\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.080 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.108 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 214/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1531/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 155/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 4636/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.021/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.43 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   70.957      1 -total\n 51.62%   36.630      1 Template:Reflist\n 48.